==Old English==
===Etymology===
Originally a plural form of a base represented by [[leod|lēod]], and closely related to [[leodan|lēodan]].  From Germanic ''*leudi'', from Indo-European ''*leudh-'' ‘to grow upwards, to surface’.  Germanic cognates include Old Saxon [[liudi]] (Dutch [[luiden]], Flemish [[lieden]]), Old High German [[liuti]] (German [[Leute]]).  The IE root is also the source of Latvian [[ļaudis]] ‘people’, Slavic ''*l’udije'' (Russian [[люди]]).

